WEBVTT

02:19.958 --> 02:21.917
Woe unto man.

02:21.917 --> 02:25.042
Brave Achilles,
slain in trial by blood...

02:25.125 --> 02:28.042
for prize,
the bride of Menelaus.

02:28.125 --> 02:31.917
And father of Antigone,
ruler of Thebes,

02:31.917 --> 02:35.917
self-rendered sightless
by lust for expiation.

02:36.042 --> 02:39.334
Lost victim
of bewildered desire.

02:39.417 --> 02:42.125
Nor has Jason's wife
fared better.

02:42.209 --> 02:46.500
Giving life only to reclaim it
in vengeful fury.

02:46.625 --> 02:49.000
For to understand
the ways of the heart...

02:49.125 --> 02:52.625
is to grasp as clearly the malice
or ineptitude of the gods,

02:52.708 --> 02:56.292
who, in their vain and clumsy labors
to create a flawless surrogate,

02:56.417 --> 02:59.417
have left mankind
but dazed and incomplete.

02:59.500 --> 03:02.500
Take, for instance,
the case of Lenny Weinrib,

03:02.583 --> 03:07.084
a tale as Greek and timeless
as fate itself.

03:07.084 --> 03:09.583
- Lenny, let's have a baby.
- Hey!

03:09.583 --> 03:12.583
A baby? Why? Because she's pregnant,
you want to have a baby?

03:12.583 --> 03:14.667
- No. It's a great idea.
- You could raise your own middleweight.

03:14.792 --> 03:16.667
- I don't want a middleweight.
- Flyweight.

03:16.792 --> 03:20.084
- No, it'd be fun.
- Have you ever had children?

03:20.084 --> 03:22.875
- No, I've never had children.
- Why not?

03:22.958 --> 03:25.792
What do you mean, "why not?" 'Cause my
first wife didn't want to have a child.

03:25.875 --> 03:28.084
- Then I never remarried really, so--
- Oh, that's great.

03:28.084 --> 03:30.084
- What am I, chopped liver?
- Until now.

03:30.167 --> 03:32.084
- Yeah?
- I never-- You didn't let me finish.

03:32.167 --> 03:34.167
- No, you'd forgotten.
- Now you've changed your mind.
You didn't want to have a child.

03:34.250 --> 03:37.875
- You should have kids.
- It's like stereo. Give him a break.

03:37.959 --> 03:40.250
- You don't want a kid?
- Oh, we--

03:40.250 --> 03:44.959
When we first met, she didn't like
the beach; she hated the Hamptons;

03:44.959 --> 03:48.334
she didn't want to have kids;
she loved the Upper East Side,
she didn't want to move.

03:48.334 --> 03:51.334
Now suddenly she's making noise about
having a kid and moving to Tribeca.

03:51.459 --> 03:54.750
- Only if the gallery moves downtown.
- Well, being pregnant is great.

03:54.750 --> 03:56.833
-  Yeah?
- I love it. You get treated
like the Queen of England.

03:56.959 --> 03:58.833
- Sure.
- You say that like it's a good thing.

03:58.959 --> 04:00.833
- Well, I like the pampering.
- She does like it.

04:00.917 --> 04:02.833
- Yeah?
- Yeah, it's fantastic.

04:02.917 --> 04:04.917
I can't give up the time
right now.

04:04.917 --> 04:07.125
There are too many exciting things
happening in my business.

04:07.251 --> 04:09.125
- So let me ask you a question.
- What?

04:09.209 --> 04:12.541
How do you plan to swing it without
being pregnant? I'm curious.

04:12.541 --> 04:14.541
- Good question. Very good question.
- No, it's easy.

04:14.625 --> 04:16.625
- We'll adopt. Oh, well.
- Mmm.

04:16.708 --> 04:18.625
- Not me. I don't want to adopt.
-  There you go.

04:18.708 --> 04:20.625
- Why not? That's a good idea.
- No. No.

04:20.708 --> 04:23.209
- You must be nuts. With, with my genes?
- Yeah?

04:23.334 --> 04:25.625
- To adopt? I have award-winning genes.
- Oh, God.

04:25.708 --> 04:28.209
- I want to pass them on.
- No, that's crazy. No, the--

04:28.292 --> 04:31.125
It's for the same reason
we don't lease a car, okay?

04:31.209 --> 04:33.125
- 'Cause it's pride of ownership.
- Okay.

04:33.209 --> 04:35.209
- And I don't want to adopt a child.
- No. Look, I'm sorry, Lenny.

04:35.292 --> 04:38.084
It's crazy 'cause the world
is full of needy kids.

04:38.209 --> 04:40.084
- You know, she's right.
-  That's true.

04:40.209 --> 04:42.084
- I know, but that-- You know, but I--
- No, I mean it.

04:42.209 --> 04:45.792
Why overpopulate the world when there
are thousands of parent-less kids?

04:45.875 --> 04:48.209
Just because you don't want
to get morning sickness, right?

04:48.209 --> 04:50.292
- No, it's not true.
- That's why you want to adopt a kid.

04:50.376 --> 04:52.500
I just can't afford
to give up a year just now.

04:52.583 --> 04:55.167
Forget it. Subject is closed.
I don't wanna--

04:55.292 --> 04:57.667
I'd be afraid that
I might get a bad seed.

04:57.667 --> 04:59.667
- Oh, you're paranoid.
- Oh, come on.

04:59.667 --> 05:02.667
That's right! What-- You read that
in the tabloids all the time.

05:02.792 --> 05:04.667
- No. A bad seed.
- That's right.

05:04.792 --> 05:07.167
Yeah, we adopt some sweet little boy,
and then he turns 13,

05:07.251 --> 05:09.875
we'd go to sleep at night,
he'd split our head open with an axe.

05:09.959 --> 05:12.875
Listen, why'd you have to
go and tell him that? You know
Lenny's got a vivid imagination.

05:12.875 --> 05:15.167
- It's a common occurrence.
- I read the same paper.
What do you want me to tell you?

05:15.251 --> 05:18.542
Anyway, what do you mean "he"?
Why can't we adopt a girl?

05:18.542 --> 05:20.667
- We're not adopting anything.
I want no sex.
- A little girl.

05:20.750 --> 05:23.251
Let the guy have a short stop
or a point guard, will ya?

05:23.251 --> 05:25.542
Can we get a check? Can we--
Can we please get out of here?

05:25.667 --> 05:27.750
I'll take the check.
I'm paying tonight.

05:27.750 --> 05:29.834
- Yes.
- You? I'm stunned.

05:29.959 --> 05:34.042
You pay, you break your record.
You-- One more and you break
DiMaggio's record-- 56 straight.

05:34.125 --> 05:36.042
That's not true.
Now, be nice.

05:36.125 --> 05:39.125
Laius, proud father, speak.

05:39.251 --> 05:42.542
I, with joy,
did have a son...

05:42.625 --> 05:45.542
so fair, so clearheaded
and brave,

05:45.625 --> 05:49.209
that I a thousand pleasures
did derive from his presence.

05:49.334 --> 05:51.209
So what happens?

05:51.334 --> 05:53.417
One day he kills me.

05:53.417 --> 05:56.334
And don't you think,
he runs off and marries my wife.

05:56.417 --> 05:59.334
Poor Oedipus, king of Thebes.

05:59.417 --> 06:02.917
My son, my son
did slay unwittingly...

06:03.000 --> 06:04.917
my noble husband...

06:05.000 --> 06:07.792
and did, without realizing,
hasten with me,

06:07.917 --> 06:10.792
his loving mother,
to lustful bed.

06:10.917 --> 06:13.126
And a whole profession
was born...

06:13.209 --> 06:15.500
charging sometimes
200 an hour,

06:15.583 --> 06:17.708
and a 50-minute hour
at that.

06:17.792 --> 06:21.209
And why a child now, out of left field?

06:21.292 --> 06:24.292
One hopes it's not to fill
some growing void in their marriage.

06:24.376 --> 06:26.292
Leave her be.

06:26.376 --> 06:29.084
A woman's urge to motherhood
is old as the earth.

06:29.209 --> 06:31.792
Children grow up;
they move out.

06:31.875 --> 06:34.875
Sometimes to ridiculous places
like Cincinnati...

06:35.000 --> 06:36.875
or Boise, Idaho.

06:37.000 --> 06:38.875
Then you never see them again.

06:38.959 --> 06:41.376
You'd think once in a while
they'd pick up a phone.

06:41.376 --> 06:44.167
But is there a growing void
in the Weinrib's marriage?

06:44.167 --> 06:46.167
We didn't say there was.

06:46.167 --> 06:49.084
We're all just speculating
on possible motives.

06:49.167 --> 06:51.167
Children are serious stuff.

06:51.167 --> 06:54.959
Look, here's a man
who killed his father...

06:55.084 --> 06:56.959
and slept with his mother.

06:57.042 --> 07:00.459
I hate to tell you what they
call my son in Harlem.

07:02.667 --> 07:04.542
Hello.

07:04.667 --> 07:08.167
- There's a baby we can adopt.
- Are you serious?

07:08.251 --> 07:11.459
I spoke to Carolyn Hester
and she's found an infant for us.

07:11.459 --> 07:14.959
- But we have to act quickly.
- I don't want a kid.

07:14.959 --> 07:17.042
Well, Lenny, you know
how hard it is.

07:17.042 --> 07:19.750
And look, the baby's
one day old, totally healthy.

07:19.834 --> 07:21.917
Unwed mother, no diseases.

07:21.917 --> 07:24.042
And it's a boy.
You wanted a boy.

07:24.126 --> 07:26.542
Amanda, I can't get
into this with you now.

07:26.625 --> 07:28.917
This is not the place
to have this discussion.

07:28.917 --> 07:31.708
I told Carolyn to be on the lookout.
She's experienced with adoptions.

07:31.708 --> 07:35.126
She knows what she's doing.
It's a boy, healthy, born this morning.

07:35.209 --> 07:37.500
No strings,
if we act quickly.

07:37.625 --> 07:40.709
Le-- Look, I-- I gotta
put my foot down.

07:40.709 --> 07:44.334
I-I-- If you want to
discuss this another time, we can.

07:44.418 --> 07:48.000
But if you gotta have a fast answer,
it's definitely "no."

07:48.000 --> 07:50.000
- Hi! Hi.

07:50.000 --> 07:52.126
- You got his head?
- He's adorable.

07:52.209 --> 07:54.418
- Yes. Oh, God.

07:54.500 --> 07:57.792
This is great. This kid is never
going to be a fighter, you know.

07:57.917 --> 08:01.875
I gotta run out and get some weights
because he's really light as a feather.

08:02.000 --> 08:04.292
- Yeah, perhaps I should have him back.
- Hi.

08:04.292 --> 08:06.376
Yeah. Maybe you better
hold him 'cause he's crying.

08:06.500 --> 08:08.376
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.
- He's crying.

08:08.500 --> 08:10.792
- Okay. Okay. It's okay. It's okay.

08:10.875 --> 08:12.792
- That's a good boy.
- That's so great.

08:12.875 --> 08:16.084
If there's any greatness in my hands,
let it pass into your body.

08:16.084 --> 08:19.875
- Get a grip on yourself.
- This kid is gonna be a great kid!

08:19.959 --> 08:21.875
- Oh, yeah.
- He's fabulous!

08:21.959 --> 08:23.875
- You're okay now.
- What do you wanna call him?

08:23.959 --> 08:25.875
- Oh, this is unbelievable. Yeah.
- Call him?

08:25.959 --> 08:29.084
- Oh, wh-- what about Eric?
- Eric? The kid's not a Viking.

08:29.167 --> 08:31.959
I wanna call him, name him,
you know, for one of my heroes.

08:32.084 --> 08:35.167
- Like what?
- I don't know. What about Groucho?

08:35.251 --> 08:38.042
- Groucho? Oh, get real.
- No, I'm serious.

08:38.167 --> 08:40.750
It's a great-- You know.
I-- I don't know. What--

08:40.875 --> 08:43.251
What about Phineas?
Do you like Phineas?

08:43.376 --> 08:45.251
Phineas?
Are you joking?

08:45.334 --> 08:47.834
Phineas is the guy who
forecloses on the mortgage.

08:47.959 --> 08:50.750
I don't want to call this kid
Phineas. He's adorable.

08:50.750 --> 08:53.834
- That's so great.
What-- What, uh-- Let me think.
- Well.

08:53.959 --> 08:55.834
- What about Django?
- Django?

08:55.959 --> 08:58.459
Django, yeah. After Django Reinhardt,
the great guitar player.

08:58.459 --> 09:02.251
- Django Weinrib?
- That's the curse of the Weinrib name.

09:02.334 --> 09:04.542
- It doesn't go with anything.
Nothing goes with Weinrib.
- Well, okay, okay.

09:04.625 --> 09:07.126
What about something simple
like, you know, Ben?

09:07.251 --> 09:09.334
- You want to call him Ben Weinrib?
- Yeah.

09:09.418 --> 09:11.709
What, he's gonna be
a-a-a gin rummy champion?

09:11.834 --> 09:14.334
- I mean, you know.
- Yeah, well, you want to deny
your heritage? Huh?

09:14.418 --> 09:16.917
Well, you know, I-I just want
the kid to have a great name.

09:17.001 --> 09:19.500
- Yeah.
- What about Sugar Ray Weinrib?

09:19.500 --> 09:21.500
Holden,
after Holden Caulfield.

09:21.500 --> 09:24.834
You see, Holden is one of those things
that works if we use your maiden name.

09:24.834 --> 09:28.418
- If it's Holden Sloane,
but not Holden Weinrib.
- Yeah.

09:28.500 --> 09:30.709
The kid is so cute!

09:30.792 --> 09:33.293
I can't believe he's--
What about Cole?

09:33.293 --> 09:36.084
- Cole?
- Cole Weinrib. Harpo Weinrib.

09:36.209 --> 09:38.709
- Harpo? No.
- How about Earl the Pearl Weinrib?

09:38.792 --> 09:41.418
- That would be so perfect.
- Oh, God! No.

09:41.500 --> 09:44.293
- Okay, what-- what about Shane?
You like the name Shane?
- Yeah.

09:44.376 --> 09:46.293
- Shane's pretty.
- Shane would be okay.

09:46.376 --> 09:50.500
On the other hand, you wouldn't want
a Supreme Court Justice called Shane.

09:50.500 --> 09:53.167
Oh, Jesus.
I got it. I got it.

09:53.167 --> 09:55.293
Brilliant.
This is so brilliant.

09:55.293 --> 09:57.293
- Got it? Ready? Are you ready?
- Mm-hmm.

09:57.293 --> 10:00.792
- Thelonius Weinrib.
- Max! What about Max?

10:00.792 --> 10:02.875
- Max?
- Yeah, Max.

10:02.875 --> 10:05.084
Max.
Oh, look how cute he is.

10:05.167 --> 10:07.459
- I wanna hold him. Max is okay.
- He's so sweet. He's smiling.

10:07.584 --> 10:09.959
- Dr. Max Weinrib. I like the name Max.
- Yeah, Max is good.

10:10.084 --> 10:13.251
- It's simple.
- How about Senator Max Weinrib?

10:13.376 --> 10:16.376
- Little tongue.
- Rabbi Max-- Rabbi Max Weinrib?

10:16.459 --> 10:18.959
No. Maybe we should
rethink Max for a minute.

10:19.042 --> 10:22.376
- Oh, he's so great.
- He's happy. I think he likes us.

10:22.459 --> 10:24.959
- He looks like you.
- He looks like me?

10:24.959 --> 10:26.459
Yeah.

10:26.459 --> 10:29.334
He looks like Broderick
Crawford a little bit.

10:55.834 --> 10:57.917
- He's so smart.
- Yeah.

10:58.001 --> 11:00.126
He picks up on everything.

11:00.209 --> 11:03.917
He's got a great personality.
You know, you wake him up,
he's always smiling and upbeat.

11:03.917 --> 11:05.917
- Like me.
- You were like that
when you were a baby.

11:05.917 --> 11:08.418
- Yeah, he's so verbal.
- Well, he's around a writer...

11:08.500 --> 11:10.500
and an art expert, right?

11:10.625 --> 11:13.126
Listen, when are you going
to move the gallery downtown?

11:13.126 --> 11:16.084
Yeah, Mother, we don't want to get
into that discussion 'cause, you know,

11:16.209 --> 11:20.293
I think we should move and Lenny
is a devoted Upper East-sider.

11:20.418 --> 11:23.376
Or shall I say is opposed
to change in any form?

11:23.500 --> 11:25.500
-  I don't know.
- It's unbelievable.

11:25.584 --> 11:29.084
The kid is unbelievable. I got him
trains, he put 'em together himself.

11:29.209 --> 11:32.168
Trains? I thought you
bought him an Erector Set.

11:32.293 --> 11:34.792
I got him an Erector Set, yeah.
And-- And I also got him this tricycle.

11:34.792 --> 11:37.376
- Wait. And the whole plastic kitchen?
- Max, I got you a tricycle.

11:37.376 --> 11:39.376
Lenny, you can't
buy him so much.

11:39.376 --> 11:41.584
- Max, I got you a tricycle.
- Look at that!

11:41.667 --> 11:44.584
- You can't buy him so much stuff.

11:44.667 --> 11:46.876
- No, no. I also got him skates.
- Skates?

11:46.876 --> 11:50.584
Yeah. And I got a couple more things
on the way in, you know.

11:50.667 --> 11:52.876
A small truck is gonna pull up
in front of the house.

11:52.959 --> 11:55.667
- What are you gonna get next year?
- Does anyone want anything to drink?

11:56.876 --> 11:58.750
- Go ahead. Shoot.

11:58.750 --> 12:00.750
Try again.

12:00.750 --> 12:03.667
You ever think about what you want
to be when you grow up, Max?

12:03.750 --> 12:07.251
Hmm, I don't know.
Maybe an interior decorator.

12:07.251 --> 12:09.542
- What?
- Just kidding, just kidding.

12:09.542 --> 12:12.042
Well, don't kid.
Here. Come on.

12:20.418 --> 12:23.334
Okay, those go in the bedroom.
Okay, you follow me.

12:23.418 --> 12:25.834
- Give me a hand with this.
- Why did we move?

12:25.917 --> 12:28.209
What do you mean,
"Why did we move?" I told you.

12:28.209 --> 12:30.834
We moved 'cause-- 'cause, you know,
'cause your mother wanted to move.

12:30.917 --> 12:35.334
'Cause, you know, the art gallery
she works at has moved downtown...

12:35.334 --> 12:37.625
and, you know,
she wanted to move.

12:37.625 --> 12:40.001
- Here's your football.
- Who's the boss between you and Mommy?

12:40.126 --> 12:43.126
- What is the question?
- Who's the boss between you and Mommy?

12:43.126 --> 12:45.126
Who is the boss?
You have to ask that?

12:45.126 --> 12:47.293
- You don't know who the boss
is between me and Mommy?
- No.

12:47.418 --> 12:51.500
I'm the boss, okay? Mommy--
Mommy's only the decision maker.

12:51.625 --> 12:54.500
You know, there's a difference
between, uh--

12:54.584 --> 12:58.584
You know, Mommy-- Mommy says
what we do and, and, uh,

12:58.709 --> 13:01.792
I have control
of the channel changer.

13:01.876 --> 13:04.293
- Here-- Here's your crayons.
- Thanks.

13:04.376 --> 13:07.584
We're new in the neighborhood
and we want Max to be really
in the best school.

13:07.709 --> 13:10.293
- Oh, but this is it.
- It's 'cause he's a very,
very bright kid.

13:10.376 --> 13:12.293
- I mean, really bright.
- Yeah, he's really great.

13:12.376 --> 13:14.792
Yes, I know. I saw his test scores
and they're wonderful.

13:14.876 --> 13:17.168
- They are. Yeah.
- I know. And he's got
a great sense of humor.

13:17.168 --> 13:20.584
- He's a sweet kid.
He's a really sweet kid.
- He's got a great personality.

13:20.667 --> 13:22.876
Wonderful. Well, I wanted to talk
to you about a special program...

13:22.959 --> 13:24.876
that we have
for bright students.

13:24.959 --> 13:26.876
- Really? And he qualifies?

13:26.959 --> 13:28.959
- Oh, yes. Absolutely.
- Sorry. Excuse me.

13:29.084 --> 13:32.251
- Certainly.
- Because-- when you hear his syntax,

13:32.376 --> 13:34.376
- Hello? Oh, hi.
- it's amazing.

13:34.376 --> 13:36.667
- Verbal skills are telling.
- His vocabulary is good,
but his syntax is--

13:36.667 --> 13:38.667
- Oh, great.
- He speaks like a grown-up.

13:38.667 --> 13:40.751
- Sorry. Lenny?
- What we can do is--

13:40.876 --> 13:43.043
- Sorry. Excuse me.
- Oh, certainly.

13:43.168 --> 13:46.667
Can we meet the Dorians tonight
for dinner at Le Cirque?

13:46.751 --> 13:50.168
The Dorians? No. Because we have
tickets to the Edward Albee play.

13:50.168 --> 13:53.625
- Listen, I can't.
- We have to.
We've been waiting for so long.

13:53.625 --> 13:56.335
You don't have to go,
but I really should go.

13:56.460 --> 13:58.542
I, uh-- No.

13:58.625 --> 14:01.542
- This will be the second time
this week we cancelled something.
- Go with Bud.

14:01.542 --> 14:04.126
- Oh, okay.
- I don't want to go with Bud.
I'm not married to Bud.

14:04.251 --> 14:06.251
Listen, go.
Can we not discuss it now?

14:06.335 --> 14:08.834
Oh, my God!
That was embarrassing.

14:08.917 --> 14:12.917
Well, just because I don't
want to have dinner yet again
with the world's dullest couple.

14:13.043 --> 14:15.209
Yeah, well, someday they may
sponsor me for my own gallery.

14:15.335 --> 14:17.209
- I said I'd go. I'm going with you.
- Yeah?

14:17.335 --> 14:19.209
But we got tickets to a show.
It's a shame.

14:19.335 --> 14:22.001
This time try and join in and don't
sit there like some zombie all night.

14:22.126 --> 14:24.418
Hey, last time I joined in,
you got angry with me.

14:24.418 --> 14:27.709
Yeah, 'cause we were discussing
the l.M. Pei Museum, not Muhammad Ali.

14:27.792 --> 14:31.126
Well, my mind wandered.
I can't keep on those topics.

14:31.209 --> 14:35.001
I just don't want to be the motor power
of the Bender Gallery forever.

14:35.084 --> 14:37.001
I want the
Amanda Sloane Gallery.

14:37.084 --> 14:40.084
Not Amanda Weinrib,
'cause there's a euphony problem.

14:40.209 --> 14:44.584
Three, four, run.
Three, four, and break the ball.

14:44.584 --> 14:46.709
-  Play 88!
- I hope they don't play like this.

14:46.792 --> 14:48.876
- 88! Ten-hut!

14:49.001 --> 14:50.876
What's the matter?
You seem down.

